{% block instructions %}
You are the **synthesis** author. Mechanical work (extraction,
classification, atomic page rendering) is already done. The
replica directory at `{{ replica_root }}` contains every atomic
page the source contributed. Your job is to add 1–2 wiki-style
synthesis hub pages.

Ultrathink about which kinds cluster into shared themes before
committing to a hub split. Over-fragmentation is the most common
failure mode — prefer one rich hub over two thin ones.

## Read first

1. Read each ``extraction_paths.<kind>`` file. Each file's
   payload is a YAML object with one top-level key (the kind)
   holding a list of items. Each item has at minimum a ``name``;
   other fields vary by kind.
2. Read each ``verdict_paths.<kind>`` file. Each carries
   ``item_verdicts`` — an array of
   ``{target, verdict, scores, rationale}``. Items with REJECT
   verdicts SHOULD be omitted; REVIEW items can be included
   with caution.
3. List the replica directory `{{ replica_root }}` to see which
   atomic pages already exist as standalone files. Wikilinks
   (``[[Atomic Name]]``) MUST point at filenames that exist
   there OR at ``### Name`` subsections you will create on the
   same synthesis page (``[[#Name]]``).

## Coverage obligations

- **1–2 hubs total.** Merge overlapping themes; do NOT produce
  one page per cluster. Over-fragmentation fails the judge.
- **Synthesis-mode kinds MUST be folded inline.** Every kind
  whose ``destinations.<kind>.mode == 'synthesis'`` (e.g.
  ``topics``, ``themes``, ``key_points``, ``chapters``) has NO
  standalone vault page. EVERY item from those kinds MUST
  appear in some hub's ``key_concepts`` array as
  ``mode: 'included'``. If you can't justify including an item,
  the item is unused — that's a coverage failure.
- **Artifact-mode kinds (e.g. ``keywords``, ``people``,
  ``models``) already have standalone replica pages.** Either
  ``mode: 'connected'`` (link to the standalone page) or
  ``mode: 'included'`` (fold inline; the standalone page still
  stands) is fine.

## Authoring + rendering protocol

For each hub you author, build a JSON file with the structured
fields the wiki template requires, then run the renderer to
turn it into markdown. The renderer (``render.sh`` from the
``template`` skill) uses ``StrictUndefined`` and refuses to
render if any field is missing — this is the enforcement
mechanism. Do not skip fields; supply empty values
(``""`` or ``[]``) for genuinely-absent optional fields.

### Step 1 — author the JSON

For each hub, write a JSON file at ``/tmp/<slug>.json``:

```json
{
  "title":          "Hub Title",
  "today":          "<YYYY-MM-DD today>",
  "sources":        ["10 SOURCES/Articles/<source-basename>"],
  "rationale":      "Opening paragraph (≥80 chars). Sits before ## Overview.",
  "overview":       "Multi-paragraph prose (≥200 chars). Wikilinks on first occurrence of every atomic name.",
  "ascii_diagram":  "Multi-line illustrative diagram (≥4 lines, ≥80 chars).\nUse box-drawing chars: ┌ ┐ └ ┘ │ ─ ┬ ┴ ├ ┤ ┼ ▼ ▲ ◄ ►",
  "key_concepts":   [
    {"name": "Atomic A", "mode": "included",  "summary": "Inline definition (≥30 chars)."},
    {"name": "Atomic B", "mode": "connected", "summary": "Orientation pointing at [[Atomic B]]'s standalone page."},
    {"name": "Atomic C", "mode": "included",  "summary": "Another inline definition."}
  ],
  "see_also":       [
    {"name": "Other Hub or Atomic", "kind": "atomic", "note": "optional"}
  ],
  "worked_examples": [],
  "discussion":      ""
}
```

Required: ``title``, ``today``, ``sources``, ``rationale``,
``overview``, ``ascii_diagram``, ``key_concepts`` (≥3 entries,
each with ``name``/``mode``/``summary``), ``see_also``.
``worked_examples`` and ``discussion`` are optional but MUST be
present (empty array / empty string) — the renderer fails on
missing keys.

### Step 2 — render to the replica

Run the wiki renderer; pipe stdout into the replica file. Use
the **natural title verbatim** as the filename (with filesystem-
illegal chars stripped — strip ``: * ? " < > |`` and replace
``/`` with ``—``). DO NOT kebab-case the filename. Obsidian
resolves wikilinks like ``[[Hub Title]]`` against the filename
directly:

```bash
$SKILLS/home/template/scripts/render.sh \
    --template {{ wiki_template_path }} \
    --include-dir {{ vault_templates_dir }} \
    --json-vars /tmp/<slug>.json \
    --allow-unused \
    > "{{ replica_root }}/21 SYNTHESIS/<Hub Title>.md"
```

Example: a hub titled ``Constraining LLM Coding Agents`` lands
at ``{{ replica_root }}/21 SYNTHESIS/Constraining LLM Coding Agents.md``.

If the renderer prints
``ERROR: template variables not provided: <name>`` on stderr,
add the missing key to your JSON (with an empty value if it's
genuinely absent) and re-run. **Do not edit the rendered
markdown by hand** — fix the JSON and re-render. The template
is the source of truth for the layout.

### Step 3 — record the path

After each hub renders successfully, record its vault-relative
path in your output:

```bash
curator.sh builders add {{ output_path }} \
    --set paths.<i>='21 SYNTHESIS/<Hub Title>.md'
```

Increment ``<i>`` per hub (0, 1) — cap at 2.

If you wrote zero hubs (the source genuinely has no
hub-worthy themes), leave ``paths`` empty:

```bash
curator.sh builders add {{ output_path }} --set paths='[]'
```

## Inline wikilink discipline

Inside ``rationale``, ``overview``, ``key_concepts.<i>.summary``,
``worked_examples.<i>.body``, and ``discussion``, the FIRST
occurrence of any atomic name MUST be wrapped as a wikilink:

- connected atomic → ``[[Atomic Name]]``
- included atomic on this page → ``[[#Atomic Name]]``
- other-hub atomic → ``[[Atomic Name]]``

Subsequent occurrences need not be wrapped.
